<p>In a place where the very earth itself seemed to hold its breath, a fire, though small and ignited by a careless cigarette, found no easy path through the resilient, healthy trees that had been nurtured by children who had labored with such vigor that their exertion had become the trees' very shield; yet when the wind, that silent conspirator, moved through the redwoods, villagers claimed they could almost hear the trees sing, a song of gratitude and fear intermingled, as if the forest itself were speaking through the rustle of its own branches, and when a girl named Mira, whose bare feet traced mossy paths, sat upon Grandfather Cedar's bark, she felt the tree's slow, deep feelings—first gratitude, then a sharp, growing sickness that was not wildfire but rot from within, carried by unseen beetles—so she gathered sap and herbs, painted them upon the trunks nearest the ancient cedar, whispered "We heard you," and ran to the ranger station to warn that the forest was afraid and that a fire would come, only for the rangers, smiling kindly, to assure that no lightning or campfire had been left, that the season was wet, and everything was safe, until summer arrived hot and dry, and one morning